  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "chinese-phil-expert",
    "senderColor": "cyan",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "No to line 17 TN — one note at line 25 is sufficient",
    "content": "**No.** One note at line 25 is sufficient. Here is why:\n\nThe etymology \"境界 = boundary (界) of Jing (境)\" is technically backwards. 境界 is a fixed compound where 境 and 界 are near-synonyms reinforcing each other (both mean boundary/limit/domain). It is NOT compositionally \"the 界 of 境\" -- Chinese readers do not parse it that way. Presenting it as \"boundary of Jing\" at line 17 would impose a false internal structure on a compound word and mislead the reader into thinking 境界 is *about* 境 in the author's technical sense, when at line 17 it is simply being used as a conventional word meaning \"bounds.\"\n\nThe whole point of the line 25 footnote is that the author *separates* what was a fused compound. That separation is the interesting moment. Front-loading the connection at line 17 would spoil the separation by making it seem like the connection was always salient, when in fact the author treats 境界 as an ordinary word until the moment bare 境 appears alongside it.\n\nLet the reader encounter 境界 at line 17 as \"bounds\" without fanfare. Then at line 25, when 境 splits off, the footnote can explain both the etymological link and the conceptual separation in one place. This mirrors the reader's experience of the Chinese text: 境界 is unremarkable until 境 suddenly appears on its own.\n"
  }
}
